# HomeCore {{VERSION}} ({{PLATFORM}})

Statically-linked musl binary. Extract this archive and you have the core
kernel, embedded MQTT broker, and Web UI in a single `homecore/` tree —
no glibc, no OpenSSL, no system dependencies.

## Layout

    homecore/
    ├── bin/homecore                # the daemon
    ├── config/
    │   ├── homecore.toml.example   # copy to homecore.toml and edit
    │   └── profiles/               # ecosystem profiles (Tasmota, Shelly, …)
    ├── ui/dist/                    # Leptos Web UI WASM bundle
    ├── scripts/
    │   └── service-templates/      # systemd unit template
    └── plugins/                    # plugin fragments extract here

## First run

    cp config/homecore.toml.example config/homecore.toml
    $EDITOR config/homecore.toml
    ./bin/homecore --config config/homecore.toml

The REST API listens on `:8080`. The embedded MQTT broker binds to
`127.0.0.1:1883` by default — read the "Security model" section of the
docs before exposing it on the LAN.

## Adding plugins

Each plugin ships as a separate `<plugin>-{{VERSION}}-{{PLATFORM}}.tar.gz`
fragment. Extract on top of this tree — the layout is designed to merge
without overwriting unrelated files:

    tar -xzf hc-hue-{{VERSION}}-{{PLATFORM}}.tar.gz       # → homecore/plugins/hc-hue/
    tar -xzf hc-yolink-{{VERSION}}-{{PLATFORM}}.tar.gz    # → homecore/plugins/hc-yolink/

Then enable each plugin in `config/homecore.toml` under its own
`[[plugins]]` block. Each plugin archive includes a README with the
specific config fields it needs.

## Verifying this archive

    sha256sum -c homecore-core-{{VERSION}}-{{PLATFORM}}.tar.gz.sha256

If verification fails, do not extract.

## systemd

`scripts/service-templates/homecore.service` is a systemd unit template.
Edit the paths inside to match your install location, then:

    sudo cp scripts/service-templates/homecore.service /etc/systemd/system/
    sudo systemctl daemon-reload
    sudo systemctl enable --now homecore.service
    sudo journalctl -u homecore.service -f

